The opponent's interpretation completely misunderstands how percentages work in student distributions. When we're told that 40% of students got below B, this is explicitly telling us about the proportion of students, not a grading threshold. This is basic set theory - if 40% are in set A (below B), then the complement set B (B and above) must contain 60% of students. Let's calculate:<tool_call>
{
    "name": math_eval,
    "arguments": {"expr": "60 * 60/100"}
}
</tool_call>
<tool_result>
{
    "name": math_eval,
    "arguments": {"expr": "60 * 60/100"},
    "result": 36.0
}
</tool_result>

The 36 students result is the only one that maintains the stated distribution of grades. The opponent's interpretation of 40% as a grade threshold contradicts the explicit wording that "40% of his Grade 5 students got a final grade below B."
